Hello TSP members! That last post concludes our 90-day program. Please check your email today for our first follow-up survey. You will receive a $20 gift card upon completion.We hope that our Facebook group has been enjoyable, educational, and life-changing in some way, whether it be a shift in your perspective towards smoking, or a commitment towards a healthier, smoke-free life. All of us at TSP have enjoyed reading your comments and interacting with you online, and we truly thank you for your participation.Although we will no longer be posting daily, you are welcome to remain in this secret group and access all of the content we've shared over the past 90 days. Try don't something new to do when you are withdrawing from smoking or thinking about something else. Keep your mind away from wanting to smoke.
Fill your free time with activities such as learning a new skill. Its hard to think about smoking when you're immersed in concentration
Using a different activity or something to replace the habit

# 12: Did you know that the number of non-smokers affected by second hand smoke is more than double the number of actual smokers in the U.S.? Who is affected by your second hand smoke?. #smokingaffectsall
Oh wow I've never thought about it like that.

I did not know that there were more people affected by second hand smoke then there are actually smokers. Family, Friends, children, and anyone that you are around when you smoke are all being affected by second hand smoke.
Wow this really just opened my eyes...especially with the people in my life I smoke around

# 11: Everyone wants to know whether electronic cigarettes can help smokers quit. Unfortunately, studies are showing that they are not any more effective than a placebo. So health professionals still recommend using well-studied strategies like counseling or nicotine replacement therapies (patch, gum) when you’re ready to quit. #ecig
Hmmmmm interesting to know
Very interesting
Very good to know.

# 10: Remember Drawback #1 ("I don't want to have withdrawal symptoms") from yesterday’s post? Which one of our following comebacks worka for you? #balance - Some withdrawal symptoms are actually signs that my body is healing - I may be coughing more because the cilia (hair-like structures that line my lungs and clean the air I breathe) that were paralyzed by the cigarette smoke are starting to work again, which makes me temporarily cough more - I may have tingling in my arms and legs because my circulation is improving
I may be coughing more
Same. Whenever I quit smoking I cough as if I'm getting sick but I know I'm not
I've noticed this I guess it's good to know it's actually a good thing

data.message: # 7: Weight gain is one of the top concerns for almost every smoker. We’ve made a list of some tips that can help keep your weight on track while you quit. Pick the one sounds good to you. How could you implement it into your life? #balance - Go for a walk, swim, bike ride or any exercise you enjoy- Find small ways to be more active, like taking the stairs instead of the elevator or parking a little farther away - Find alternatives to snacking, like calling a friend - Drink some extra water
I would do all of the above. I am already doing all of the above.
That's great for you, 10118!
I would choose to be more active and start jogging/ running daily
#6: What would be the best-case scenario if you quit smoking? #balance
Saving my hard earned money to put toward other things. Along with a better quality of life plus better health overall
Being able to run without wanting to die afterwards
I agree with 10118 . just being in overall better physical health
Hi everyone and welcome to TSP! I am available for the next hour. Let me know if you have any questions! #TDII
How much does smoking cigarettes regularly actually raise your chances of developing cancerous cells

I am not sure about the exact numbers for cancer, but the overall chances of dying prematurely because of smoking are about 50% for regular smokers. So one in two smokers will die because of it and by that I mean about 20 years early on average. What's your initial reaction to this information?
Here is some more comprehensive information on the science behind those numbers if you are interested. Let me know if you have any questions! http://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMsa1211128
I've got to run guys - see you next week.

Honestly you get just as addicted to the ecigs so the are lining there pockets either way
To keep us as loyal customers
They put out ecigs and vapes to make sure to keep us smoking. Whether its cigs or vapes we keep giving them our hard earned money until we actually stop buying in to their circle of profit

#4: For any of you who aren’t sure what an e-cig is, take a look at this FDA page explaining what they are and some of the controversy surrounding their regulation. If you were a minor, do you think an e-cig would be more appealing and “safer” to try than a traditional cigarette? #beingconscious
If I were a minor I would think they were more appealing and safer.
When I was a minor in highschool they were more appealing to most people. It is safer for the lungs as well
